[4] California (Los Angeles County): UCLA and Cal State LA quarantine declared
Date: Fri 26 Apr 2019 3:07 AM ET
Source: National Public Radio (NPR) [abridged, edited]
https://tinyurl.com/y49xxgg4


Hundreds of students and faculty at 2 universities in Los Angeles (LA) have been asked to stay home unless they can prove that they've been vaccinated against measles. The LA campuses of the University of California and California State University imposed the quarantine after they became aware of people infected with measles who had potentially exposed hundreds. At UCLA, a student exposed at least 500 people earlier this month [April 2019]; at Cal State, someone with measles went to a library and encountered hundreds.

UCLA was notified by the LA County Department of Public Health that one of its students had contracted measles. After identifying people the infected student might have come in contact with while contagious, the school asked them to provide proof of immunization. On Wednesday [24 Apr 2019], 119 people who couldn't provide proof were quarantined.

Of those, dozens were able to prove immunity and were released from quarantine by Thursday [25 Apr 2019] afternoon. But 82 were still quarantined, and "a few may need to remain in quarantine for up to 7 days," the school said in a statement.

"Considering the time that has elapsed since the last possible exposure to the individual with measles on 9 Apr 2019, the highest risk period for developing measles has already passed -- and the period during which symptoms may appear is nearing the end," UCLA Chancellor Gene Block said.

At Cal State, 156 library employees, some of them students, were quarantined after they couldn't provide their immunization records, The Associated Press reported.

Los Angeles County declared Monday [22 Apr 2019] that the county was facing a measles outbreak, with international travel leading to 5 case of measles in California, state officials said, according to the Los Angeles Times.

[Byline: Matthew S. Schwartz]

