[7] California (Butte County): measles on top of wildfires
Date: Sun 21 Apr 2019
Source: Press Herald [abridged, edited]
https://www.pressherald.com/2019/04/21/measles-outbreak-tests-health-workers-already-stretched-thin-by-wildfire/


Northern California health workers are scrambling to control a growing measles outbreak centered on a region that is still reeling from the most destructive wildfire in state history. In November [2018], the Camp fire decimated the town of Paradise, killed 85 people and left behind billions of dollars in damage. Butte County, about 90 miles north of Sacramento, continues to grapple with the consequences of the blaze.

So the arrival of measles seems to residents like just the latest in a string of bad luck. As of Fri [19 Apr 2019], at least 15 Californians had been diagnosed with measles as part of the outbreak that began last month [March 2019] in Butte County, according to health officials. "It feels like we keep getting hit with a new disaster every few months," said Cassie Miracle, who runs a health coalition in Chico, the biggest city in Butte County.

The Butte County outbreak began when a man caught measles in March [2019] during a trip to the Philippines, where thousands of people have come down with the disease this year [2019]. The outbreak has expanded outside Butte to Placer, Tehama and Shasta counties.

In California, 23 people statewide have been diagnosed with measles this year [2019], according to state data released Thursday [18 Apr 2019]. Though the Butte County outbreak is the largest cluster, there have been a smattering of cases around the state.

[Byline: Soumya Karlamangla]

