[8] New York (Rockland County): 2nd emergency declared
Date: Thu 25 Apr 2019 5:24 PM EDT
Source: WABC [abridged, edited]
https://abc7ny.com/health/rockland-declares-2nd-emergency-over-measles-outbreak/5270743/


Rockland County Executive Ed Day issued a 2nd declaration of a local State of Emergency [Thu 25 Apr 2019] amid the measles outbreak, renewing the original declaration that was due to expire at 11:59 PM. The renewed State of Emergency takes effect at midnight [Fri 26 Apr 2019] and will remain in effect until 11:59 PM, Sat 25 May 2019.

The new emergency declaration does not contain the Measles Outbreak Emergency Directive, which prohibited non-vaccinated persons from entering indoor places of public assembly. That directive was overturned by a judge, and subsequent appeals have been denied.

However, the Rockland County Department of Health will continue to enforce the new Commissioner's Orders that were announced last week, which mandates that anyone with measles or anyone exposed to the illness avoid public spaces or face a USD 2000-a-day fine.

"Over the last 30 days since my original declaration we have lost the one thing we couldn't afford to lose, valuable time," Day said. "With nearly 50 new confirmed cases in less than a month, what we predicted has come true -- this outbreak continues to rage despite the best efforts of our Department of Health."

The order also applies to students who are required to have the proper MMR immunizations and to date have not demonstrated that the vaccines have been administered. This does not apply to students with medical or religious exemptions.

"The disagreement amongst the various courts has undoubtedly caused confusion and contributed to this situation continuing," Day said. "However, I pledge that we will continue to do everything within our power to combat this deadly disease and bring it to a stop once and for all."

Officials say 19 279 MMR vaccinations have been given within Rockland County since the outbreak began in October 2018. There have been no fatalities amid the current outbreak, and only 3 measles-related deaths in the US in the past 2 decades.

Watch the full news conference by County Executive Ed Day: https://youtu.be/cT3Nkevn7gE.

