[17] Nigeria (Borno)
Date: Sun 21 Apr 2019
Source: Leadership [abridged, edited]
https://leadership.ng/2019/04/21/measles-kills-17-in-borno-10000-others-infected/


No fewer than 17 children within the age bracket of 6 months to 5 years have been confirmed dead while 10 000 cases were recorded within 14 weeks of a measles outbreak in Borno State. The Director, Disease Control, under the State Primary Health Development Agency, Babagana Abiso, disclosed this in an interview with leadership on Sunday [21 Apr 2019] in Maiduguri, the Borno State capital.

Abiso said government is conducting reactive vaccination in prioritised 15 local government areas of the state to children aged 6 months to 6 years to curtail the outbreak. He said: "We have an outbreak of measles in the state and this started from week 1 of January [2019], and by week 14, we had recorded nearly 10 000 cases all over the state. And the disease, you know, affects children. We have recorded 17 deaths. The government is making efforts to conduct reactive vaccination against measles in the affected areas.

"Because of shortage of vaccine, we visited only Maiduguri Metropolitan Council (MMC) to commence the vaccination. We have covered about 8 wards that are seriously affected, and for the remaining 12 local government areas, as soon as we receive vaccines from the national level, we will ensure that all the prioritised areas get vaccination."

He said those mostly affected by measles are children aged 6 months to 5 years, noting that the state decided to extend the vaccination to children aged 6 years so as not to take any chances. Meanwhile, when our correspondent visited the measles section of the State Specialist Hospital, Maiduguri, a good number of children severely hit by the disease were on admission, with the outpatients administered with drugs and discharged.

A doctor on duty, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said even though the disease is rampant during heat, the cause could also be attributed to the influx of internally displaced persons (IDPs) whose children were not vaccinated before fleeing their communities.

[Byline: Francis Okoye]

